<HEADLINE>
<P>
BAJA GOVERNOR QUITS JOB EARLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The governor of Baja California said Tuesday that he will step down early to 
take a position with a federal banking agency negotiating to reduce Mexico's 
foreign debt. 
</P>
<P>
The surprise announcement by Xicontencatl Leyva Mortera at a press conference 
in Mexicali, the state capital, fueled speculation that he is being forced out 
by Mexico's new president, Carlos Salinas de Gortari. Leyva's term was to 
extend to the end of October, 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Some Baja commentators have suggested that political leaders in Mexico City are 
unhappy with Leyva, whose five-year administration has been marked by several 
prominent scandals and political defeats. In July, 1988, Salinas was defeated 
in Baja by leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
