<HEADLINE>
<P>
INFANT MORTALITY AT RECORD LOW, CUBA SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HAVANA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cuba's infant mortality rate has dropped to 12 per 1,000 live births, its 
lowest level ever and one of the 20 lowest in the world, the state-run Prensa 
Latina news agency said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Infant mortality was 60 per 1,000 in 1959, when the average life expectancy of 
a Cuban was 50 years compared with 74 now. Health care has been one of the 
priorities of the Cuban revolution, which marks its 30th anniversary this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
