<HEADLINE>
<P>
AUTO INSURANCE CONTROVERSY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the automobile insurance companies profess to be seeking to hold down 
costs, my recent experience indicates the contrary. The approach utilized by my 
insurance company is structured to unnecessarily encourage higher repair costs 
and thus "justify" higher insurance premiums and correspondingly greater 
profits. The process needs to be changed if insurance costs are to be cut. 
</P>
<P>
The higher than required expenditures result from the way the repair work is 
authorized. After a recent accident, two bids of $1,100 and $1,000 were 
obtained for repairing the damage to my vehicle. The company's adjuster 
authorized $1,495. The company's instructions called for the insured (myself) 
to take the adjuster's authorization to the repair shop, a mistake. The repair 
shop then magically found additional work that had to be done which escalated 
the cost up to the amount authorized, $1,494 in my case. Inasmuch as I knew my 
insurance rates were going to go up because of the accident and not because of 
an expenditure related to the cost of repairing my car, and the company 
reimburses 100% of costs over the deductible, there was no motivation to keep 
costs in line. The result is that those insured by the company are going to be 
asked to indirectly pay for nearly $500 in unnecessary repair costs in the form 
of higher premiums. 
</P>
<P>
Had my insurance company structured its rates and reimbursement schedule to 
provide for the insured to pay a percentage of the costs in addition to the 
deductible, as is typically the case for most medical insurance, all parties 
would have been better motivated to keep costs in line. The insurance companies 
need to realize that unless they encourage cost savings, the pressure to 
dictate an arbitrary premium reduction will continue unabated. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL N. ERNSTOFF 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
