<HEADLINE>
<P>
BROKERAGE BUYS CONTROL OF IRVINE'S CYCLE INDUSTRIES; 
</P>
<P>
MERRILL LYNCH TURNS BULLISH ON SURFWEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY ANN GALANTE, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Merrill Lynch is hitting the surf. 
</P>
<P>
The big brokerage house with the button-down image has become majority owner of 
an Irvine company that owns Off Shore Sportswear, a surfwear manufacturer, and 
holds licenses to produce Hobie T-shirts and Catchit T-shirts. 
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch Pierce Fenner &amp; Smith bought the interest in Cycle Industries 
-- and its surfwear labels -- several weeks ago from Steve MacBaisey, Cycle's 
founder. MacBaisey, Cycle employees and Ex-Sto Capital, an investment banking 
house, also own interests in Cycle, MacBaisey said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
MacBaisey on Tuesday confirmed reports of the sale, which was completed in 
November, but declined to reveal financial details. Merrill Lynch officials 
could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
MacBaisey will continue to run the company as chairman, chief executive and 
president under a 4-year management contract. 
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch's entree into surfwear marks the second major shake-up recently 
in the volatile industry, which has hit rough waters in the last 2 years. 
</P>
<P>
Catchit -- a Tustin-based manufacturer of surf trunks, board shorts and a 
women's line called Haute Rush -- was sold Dec. 22 for an undisclosed sum by 
Pacific Trail of Seattle to its founder and president, Ian Forman, and two 
other investors. The company has been in a slump for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
Catchit owns the rights to its T-shirt line and now will collect royalties from 
its sub-licensees, including Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
The changes are seen as more evidence of a financial wipeout within the 
$1-billion-a-year surfwear business. 
</P>
<P>
"There's been an oversaturation of the beach look in the marketplace, and it's 
a cyclical industry," said Glenn Mounger, president of the Mounger Corp. in 
Seattle, parent company of Pacific Trail. "When everybody jumps on a product, 
the uniqueness isn't there. The consumer got tired of it." 
</P>
<P>
Forman, the Catchit founder, acknowledged that the firm's sales were "flat" 
last year and that the company lost money. 
</P>
<P>
Burbank-based Hobie Apparel -- which licenses its entire line, including 
T-shirts -- has retail sales of about $120 million and is doing well -- 
particularly in such chains as Mervyn's and J.C. Penney, industry observers 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Both Off Shore and Catchit have suffered among surfwear retailers in the last 2 
years, according to some industry insiders. 
</P>
<P>
"Off Shore and Catchit mean nothing -- they've been gone for years," said Paul 
Heussenstamm, owner of Newport Surf &amp; Sport in Newport Beach, a leading 
retailer and industry trend-setter. "Two years ago, I used to buy a ton from 
Catchit. But their line got real bad -- bad design, bad quality, poor taste." 
</P>
<P>
To revive the lines, Merrill Lynch and MacBaisey will have to increase sales of 
the labels to such major retail outlets as Walmart, Sears and J.C. Penney, 
Heussenstamm said. 
</P>
<P>
While he declined to discuss strategy, MacBaisey predicted that Cycle 
Industries' sales will climb 25% in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Cycle was founded as a silk-screening company by MacBaisey about 10 years ago. 
Today, about 65% of its business is silk-screening of clothing made by others, 
MacBaisey said, while the remaining 35% is manufacturing, including the Off 
Shore line of surfwear. 
</P>
<P>
Industry sources estimated Cycle's retail revenue at $30 million to $40 million 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
According to MacBaisey, Cycle is "probably the most profitable garment 
manufacturer in California." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
MERRILL LYNCH &amp; CO; ACQUISITIONS; CYCLE INDUSTRIES INC; OFFSHORE OF 
CALIFORNIA (COMPANY); CATCHIT INC; PACIFIC TRAIL INC; MOUNGER CORP; HOBIE 
APPAREL INC 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
