<HEADLINE>
<P>
SWEDISH DAVIS CUP LEADER QUITS AFTER DEFEAT BY GERMANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
STOCKHOLM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Swedish Davis Cup captain Hans Olsson announced today he was quitting after 
Sweden, boasting two of the world's top-ranked players, lost to West Germany in 
the cup final last month. 
</P>
<P>
Olsson, the nonplaying captain who led Sweden to three Davis Cup titles since 
1984, was replaced by John-Anders (Jonte) Sjogren. 
</P>
<P>
Olsson cited time pressures and his unwillingness to travel with the team as 
his reason for stepping down. 
</P>
<P>
Sjogren coaches Mats Wilander, winner of last year's Australian, French and 
U.S. Opens. 
</P>
<P>
Olsson came under fierce criticism after the Davis Cup team, led by Wilander 
and 1988 Wimbledon winner Stefan Edberg, lost 4-1 on indoor clay at home in 
Goteborg to a powerful German squad headed by Boris Becker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
